Paul saw this with his own eyes, and "his spirit was stirred in him" (Acts 17:15). No emotion but animosity was aroused in him by the image of a goddess with beautiful skin surrounded by the lovely green of the Judas tree and the young leaves of the sycamore which rustle in a gentle breeze. The scattered blossoms of violets and roses around the stone pedestal, the flicker of honeybees in flight---even these smallest works of nature, how much more full they are of precious life than any idol made by the hand of man! He became agitated and went to preach to the people in the agora. He encounters an Epicurean philosopher. When he attacks the superstition of idols, the philosopher agrees with him, confirming the harm of idols. Encouraged by this, he preaches Jesus' resurrection. The philosopher suddenly becomes zealous and rebuts him by saying that faith in the immortality of the soul is nothing but a delusion, and human happiness depends on doing away with it. Paul asks him if he did not revere the Almighty Creator. The philosopher replies that the world is no more than the fusion and fragmentation of atoms and that nothing ought be revered more than pleasures of this world. Paul begins to speak with increasing passion about how the existence of eternal life was proved by his own experiences. The curious Athenians---the Athenians who "spent their time in nothing else, but either to tell or to hear some new thing" (Act 17:21)---take an unusual interest in the introduction of another new god, and so they bring Paul to the judgment seat of Areopagus. Many citizens had gathered there to listen to a case. With the verdict reached, Paul is summoned as entertainment. \
