<!--\'b6 15. --> The materialist theory that could never allow for the resurrection of Christ is now the common sense of mankind. The only authority that folk tales like the creation of the world in seven days by God have is now that of "folk tales." The virgin birth is no more than a mad fantasy. Faith in the Son of God has nothing to it beyond empty metaphysical theorizing, even in its symbolic meaning. The world surely develops from the fusion and fragmentation of fundamental elements, as the atomists of old saw. The soul is product of the body and perishes with it. As death is the cessation of activity and the dissolution of living tissue, there is no way for there to be life after death. Averting one's eyes from these facts and positing the existence of God or life after death is no more than the behavior of a coward who cannot accept apparent reality as it is.---For minds following this kind of common sense, proclaiming "God is dead" and the like is no longer stimulating: God never existed in the first place. Hence humanity conducts its way of living with the satisfaction of the desires in this present life as its sole aim. There is no restraint beyond utilitarian moderation for the sake of yet greater satisfaction. \
