<!--\'b6 16. --> However, can a person be at peace in this material world without dissatisfaction? When he has the joys of love, does he not hope for the eternality of bliss? After physical pleasure, is he not pained by its ephemerality? As he patiently endures pain and suffering, can he be pleased with the thought that this life is no more than physiological happenstance?---That many answer these questions with "No" is to be understood. At the same time, it is hard to deny that there are also significant numbers who answer with "Yes." Thus, the questions get updated: Does a person not naturally seek after deep mysteries beyond common sense? The mystery of love, the mystery of the physical, the bottomless depths of life: does one not try to take hold of these things? Surely in former times all people embraced these demands in their breasts at least once. Some ended up allowing their whole heart to be occupied by these demands. He who enters on the path of science cannot help but be struck by the wondrous and unknowable power that appears in the subtle laws of nature and human life. He who acts as a philosopher comes to a shocking realization of the breadth of the world, which stretches beyond the bounds of human wisdom in the infinite creative power of life.---Thus, idols are once again being sought after.\
