<!--\'b6 20. --> I myself was a born rebel, to the best of my knowledge. As a child in primary school, my mind was full of criticism for Kusunoki,[^] and as a young man in middle school, I cursed the presumption and spiritlessness of my teachers. In an age that took no mind of the authority of educators, I sneered at my classmates' school spirit and scorned their zeal for scholastic inquiry. And I felt an unusual interest in looking down on what went by the name of morality. It was only because religion had no controlling authority over me that I approached it willingly, but I certainly never entered the mental state in which one has to feel some of its authority. Rather, to me it was only a tool to use in rebellion against other authorities. Finally, I took an attitude of rebellion even toward the authority of ways of life themselves. I took joy in smiling coldly at love though I had no prior experience of profound love; I applauded the death of God though I had never felt the pressure of clerical authority. For me at that time, it was the highest way of life for a human being. So I still had no inkling that my moods and thoughts had gradually degenerated into a caricature of a modern iconoclast.\
